Task 1: Label and Data Leakage Identification

Label Column: repeat_purchase_flag
Justification: This column represents the target outcome we are trying to predict 
(whether a customer makes a repeat purchase within 30 days).
Data Leakage Column: discount_used_on_repeat_order
Justification: This column introduces data leakage because it contains information about the repeat purchase itself 
(the discount applied), which is unknown at the time of prediction and only exists after the target event has occurred. 

Task 2: Recommended Pre-modeling Steps

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
Why it matters: EDA helps visualize data distributions, identify missing values, and uncover anomalies or outliers that, 
if ignored, can degrade model performance. It also helps detect multicollinearity between features, ensuring the model isn't 
confused by redundant information.

Train/Test Split (specifically Time-Based Splitting)
Why it matters: Because this is a predictive task based on time (30-day window), splitting data chronologically 
is crucial to avoid "temporal leakage," where future information leaks into the past. Using a random split 
might use information from "future" customers to predict "past" customers, leading to over-optimistic results.

Feature Engineering and Scaling
Why it matters: Converting raw data into meaningful features—such as converting days_since_last_order into
categorical buckets or scaling monetary values—improves the model's ability to identify patterns. 
While Gradient Boosting is robust, engineering can simplify the learning process and reduce noise.
